04685nam a22005295i 9780824861261DE-B159720210225050953.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210225t20062006hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248612617 a10.1515/97808248612612doi  a(DE-B1597)484395  a(OCoLC)1024061758  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aPL402b.C63 2007eb 7aFOR0030002bisacsh04a494/.238132221 aCoblin, W. South, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Handbook of 'Phags-Pa Chinese /cW. South Coblin. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (326 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aABC Chinese Dictionary Series ;v1800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tI. The 'Phags-pa Chinese Script: Its Invention, Textual Attestation, and Historical Background -- tII. A Brief Review of 'Phags-pa Chinese Studies -- tIII. Analysis and Interpretation of the 'Phags-pa Alphabet -- tIV. A Structural and Historical Consideration of the 'Phags-pa Chinese Sound System -- tGlossary of 'Phags-pa Chinese Forms -- tPīnyīn Index to Chinese Characters in the Glossary -- tStroke Order Index to Chinese Characters in the Glossary -- tIndex of Transliterated 'Phags-pa Orthographic Forms in the Glossary -- tReferences -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPhags-pa Chinese is the earliest form of the Chinese language to be written in a systematically devised alphabetic script. It is named after its creator, a brilliant thirteenth-century Tibetan scholar-monk who also served as political adviser to Kublai Khan. 'Phags-pa's invention of an alphabet for the Mongolian language remains an extraordinarily important accomplishment, both conceptually and practically. With it he achieved nothing less than the creation of a unified script for all of the numerous peoples in the Mongolian empire, including the Central Asian Turks and Sinitic-speaking Chinese.'Phags-pa is of immense importance for the study of premodern Chinese phonology. However, the script is difficult to read and interpret, and secondary materials on it are scattered and not easily obtained. The present book is intended as a practical introduction to 'Phags-pa Chinese studies and a guide for reading and interpreting the script. It consists of two parts. The first part is an introductory section comprising four chapters. This is followed by a glossary of 'Phags-pa Chinese forms and their corresponding Chinese characters, together with pinyin and stroke order indexes to those characters.The first introductory chapter outlines the invention of the 'Phags-pa writing system, summarizes the major types of material preserved in it, and describes the historical and linguistic contexts in which this invention occurred. Following chapters detail the history of 'Phags-pa studies, the alphabet and its interpretation, and the salient features of the underlying sound system represented by the script, comparing it with those of various later forms of Chinese that have been recorded in alphabetic sources. A Handbook of 'Phags-pa Chinese will be of special interest to Chinese historical phonologists and scholars concerned with the history and culture of China and Central Asia during the Yuan period (A.D. 1279–1368).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 0a'Phags-pa alphabetvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 0aMongolian languagexAlphabetvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 0aMongolian languagexPhonologyvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 7aFOREIGN LANGUAGE STUDY / Chinese.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHawaii eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486126140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9